Part 10

The new manufacturing plant at Nandyal sat on twelve acres of former cotton land. The soil was still bright red, showing between the grey concrete foundations of the bottling unit like dried blood on concrete. 

A tall chain-link fence ran all the way around the property. The top of the fence carried three tight strands of galvanized barbed wire that caught the glare of the morning sun.

Vikram sat in his brown leatherette chair. It was no longer located in the two rooms above the spare-parts godown. 

Suresh had moved it to the new administrative wing, a room that smelled of fresh paint, synthetic floor glue, and the air conditioning that hummed from a white box on the wall. 

Suresh had tried to leave the chair behind. "It looks bad, sir," he had said, pointing at the cracked armrests. "The visitors from the state capital—they sit on the new leather in the lobby, then they come in here and see this."

"The visitors don't pay the loaders' wages," Vikram said.

"Still, sir," Suresh protested.

"Leave it," Vikram said.

So the chair had stayed. The stuck wheel that listed the chair two degrees to the left had already made a dark, curved streak on the new grey linoleum floor.

---

From his wide window, Vikram could see the entire loading bay. Twelve multi-axle trucks were lined up in the red dust, their engines idling, the grey exhaust smoke rising straight up in the windless heat. 

The loaders were mostly local boys from the villages near the hills. They wore faded blue shirts with the company logo printed on the pocket—a simple black malt grain.

A boy of about eighteen was sitting on a wooden crate near the rear tyre of the third truck. He was eating curd rice from a steel tiffin box.

His hands were white with the dust of the cement packing. He used his fingers to scoop the rice quickly, looking at the security gate every few seconds as if he expected a guard to tell him to move.

Vikram watched him from the window.

He remembered table seven in the dissection hall. He remembered the sharp smell of formaldehyde. 

Back then, he was a student who had wanted to know the names of the muscles in the human arm so he could heal them. 

Now, he knew the names of the local load-unions. He knew how many bags of barley a truck could carry before the highway police demanded a bribe at the border.

The boy near the truck finished his rice, closed the steel tiffin box, and wiped his fingers on the side of the wooden crate. He stood up, adjusted his blue shirt, and went back to the loading ramp.

The signature of Ahuja Sahib on the clearance ledger had given that boy a tiffin box and a faded blue shirt. It was a good thing.

But as Vikram watched the truck move slowly toward the gate, the dust rising to cover the red cotton fields, he felt only the weight of it. 

The fourteen hundred crore was a number on a page. The twelve acres was a map in the land register. 

But the text in the ledger didn't say how many more boys would have to spend their afternoons in the red Nandyal dust to make the numbers match.

[End of Part 10]
